## 1. Definitions

### 1.1 "Licensor"
"Licensor" means **Zippy Technologies LLC**, located at **1515 E Lewis,
Wichita, Kansas 67211, Sedgwick County, Kansas, United States**.

### 1.2 "Product"
"Product" means the software product known as the **Zippy Mesh LLM Router**.

### 1.3 "Software"
"Software" means the Product and all related source code, object code,
binaries, libraries, modules, SDKs, scripts, build logic, packaging,
deployment artifacts, configuration, documentation, examples, interfaces,
assets, and other materials contained in or distributed through the
repositories listed in the Product and Repository Scope section above,
together with any updates, upgrades, revisions, patches, fixes, and portions
thereof made available by Licensor.

### 1.4 "Open Materials"
"Open Materials" means only those files or portions of the Software expressly
designated by Licensor as open under this License, whether by:
- inclusion in `COMPONENTS.md` or another Licensor-issued classification
  manifest,
- a file header or repository notice stating **"ZIPPY OPEN MATERIAL"**,
- placement in a directory expressly designated by Licensor as open, or
- another written designation by Licensor.

### 1.5 "Restricted Materials"
"Restricted Materials" means all Software that is not expressly designated as
Open Materials. All Software is Restricted Material unless explicitly
identified as Open Material by Licensor.

### 1.6 "Personal Use"
"Personal Use" means use by a natural person for private, hobbyist,
experimental, evaluation, or other non-commercial purposes, and not on behalf
of any company, employer, customer, organization, revenue-generating activity,
or operational environment.

### 1.7 "Educational Use"
"Educational Use" means use by a student, instructor, school, university,
academic lab, or researcher solely for teaching, coursework, classroom
demonstration, training, or non-commercial academic research, and not for
commercial services, paid consulting, production operations, internal business
deployment, or product development for sale or commercial rollout.

### 1.8 "Commercial Use"
"Commercial Use" means any use that is not Personal Use or Educational Use,
including without limitation:
- internal business or organizational use,
- production use by a company, contractor, public entity, or nonprofit acting
  in an operational or service-delivery capacity,
- SaaS, hosted, managed, API, inference, gateway, orchestration, routing, or
  middleware services whether or not directly charged to end users,
- resale, white-labeling, OEM, embedding, sublicensing, or customer delivery,
- monetized products or services,
- commercial pilots, staging, pre-production, benchmarking, or testing
  performed for a business purpose,
- use by a consultant, integrator, MSP, reseller, or contractor for a paying
  client or commercial engagement.

### 1.9 "Install"
"Install" means each individual installation, deployment, runtime instance,
provisioned instance, production node, customer-dedicated instance, or
separately instantiated copy of the Software used for Commercial Use,
including:
- each physical server or appliance,
- each virtual machine,
- each container or pod replica used to deliver service,
- each production runtime node,
- each edge node or customer-site deployment,
- each on-premises customer deployment,
- each separately installed embedded copy.

Ephemeral CI/CD jobs used solely to build or test the Software for less than
twenty-four (24) hours are not counted as Installs unless they provide or
support a commercial runtime service. Development instances used internally by
a single developer solely to develop, test, or evaluate the Software for
potential Commercial Use are not counted as Installs, provided no end-user
traffic is served through them.

### 1.10 "Derivative Work"
"Derivative Work" means any modification, adaptation, translation, port,
enhancement, extension, patch, improvement, reimplementation, fork, branch,
merge, or other work based on, derived from, or incorporating a material part
of the Software, whether or not the result would qualify as a derivative work
under applicable copyright law.

### 1.11 "Disclosure Package"
"Disclosure Package" means the complete corresponding source code of a
Derivative Work together with: build instructions, dependency manifests,
change summaries, and documentation sufficient for Licensor to understand,
build, and evaluate the Derivative Work.

### 1.12 "Contribution"
"Contribution" means any work of authorship submitted to Licensor for
inclusion in or improvement of the Software, including source code, bug fixes,
documentation, examples, and test cases, submitted voluntarily by any means.

